Heart Disease Prediction Using Logistic Regression and Decision Tree Classification¶

Bei Wang, PhD student in epidemiology at dpt of PHS

02/26/2022

Task¶

My task is a binary classification of heart disease using the Heart Disease Dataset from the UCI repositories among about 900 individuals. The target was coded as a binary varible indicating the presence of heart disease. 13 features in the demographic and biomarker aspects are available for predicting heart disease.

Data source: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/heart+disease

Link to the recording to my presentation: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1vlpYFx6In8ZPlY46ua_8V6XjlV-dneZR/view?usp=sharing

2.2 Imputation and feature selection¶

Based on the missing value table above, I will drop 'slope', 'ca', and 'thal' because more than 30% of the data are missing in these variables. Also, drop 'num' as it's replaced by the target variable created. I end up with 10 predictors to use now.

In [15]:
drop= ['slope', 'ca', 'thal','num']
heart= heart[heart.columns.drop(drop)]

For the rest of the features, I will impute with the most frequent values of each feature.

In [16]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
imputer=SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
heart = pd.DataFrame(imputer.fit_transform(heart), columns=heart.columns)

def rank_corr_pair (df, n):
    corr= df.corr().abs().unstack()
    corr= corr.sort_values(ascending=False)
    return corr[0: n]

2.3 Examine and one-hot code categorical features¶

There are 5 out of 10 features(predictors) that should be treated as categrical as listed below. I create 2 versions of dummy variables. For logistic regression, I need to drop a category of each categorical feature as a reference category, so that the coefficients correctly represents the log odds ratio of the other categories compared to the reference category. Another version of dummy varibles does not drop categories as such.

  • sex: 1(male); 0(female)
  • cp(chest pain type): 1(typical angina); 2(atypical angina); 3(non-anginal pain); 4(asymptomatic)
  • restecg(resting electrocardiographic): 0(normal); 1(having ST-T wave abnormality); 2(showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes' criteria)
  • fbs(fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl): 1(true); 0(false)
  • exang(exercise induced angina): 1(yes); 0(no)

# create dummy variables for the categorical features, the first level of each categorical feature was dropped 
cat_vars= heart[['sex', 'cp', 'restecg', 'fbs', 'exang']]
# drop a category of the dummy varibles for logistic regression
ohe= OneHotEncoder(drop= "first")
ohe.fit(cat_vars)
cat_ohe= ohe.transform(cat_vars).toarray()
cat_ohe= pd.DataFrame(cat_ohe, columns= ohe.get_feature_names(cat_vars.columns), index= heart.index)

# do not drop for decision tree classification 
ohe1= OneHotEncoder()
ohe1.fit(cat_vars)
cat_ohe1= ohe1.transform(cat_vars).toarray()
cat_ohe1= pd.DataFrame(cat_ohe1, columns= ohe1.get_feature_names(cat_vars.columns), index= heart.index)

The fewer feature version will be used for logistic regression while the largers one used for decision tree classification

General models selection steps¶

  • Hyper-parameter tuning: apply GridSearch and a 10-folds cross validation in the training set to select the best model
  • Evaluate the best model performance in the test set that was set aside
In [35]:

from sklearn.model_selection import  GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

4. Summary and conclusion¶

Through hyper-parameter tuning and 10-folds cross validation, the best models selected by logistic regression and decision tree have an AUC score of 0.87 and 0.82, respectively. They both have pretty high performance. The decision tree classifier narrowed down to only 4 features, greatly reducing the complexity and model variance. So the decision tree classifier is more optimal compared to logistic regression model in this task of heart disease classification.

Logistic regression¶

From the logistic regression, we can see that several features are more important, such as sex, chest pain type, and exercise induced angina. This is consistent with the decision tree classifier.

In [50]:
def plot_feature_importance(importance, names, model_type):
    feature_importance= np.array(importance)
    feature_names= np.array(names)
    df= pd.DataFrame({
        'Feature names': feature_names,
        'Feature importance': feature_importance
    })
    df= df.sort_values(by= 'Feature importance', ascending=False, key= pd.Series.abs)#sort by absolute values 
    #plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    sns.barplot(x=df['Feature importance'], y= df['Feature names'])
    plt.title(model_type + ' feature importance')
    plt.xlabel('Feature importance')
    plt.ylabel('Feature names')

Decision tree¶

The decision tree classfier retained only 4 features, which are exercise induced angina, asymptomatic angina, male, and maximum heart rate achieved. They seem to be variables that are easy to collect among people who are at risk of heart disease.
